data.content:
## What Breaks in .NET 11

In .NET 11, EF Core's Cosmos DB provider **removes the sync-over-async opt-in entirely**. All synchronous LINQ operators (`ToList()`, `First()`, `Count()`) and `SaveChanges()` now throw `InvalidOperationException` at runtime.

Your four methods all break:

| Method | Throws because |
|--------|---------------|
| `ToList()` | Sync enumeration removed |
| `First()` | Sync enumeration removed |
| `Count()` | Sync enumeration removed |
| `SaveChanges()` | Sync persistence removed |

## The Fix — Convert to Async

```csharp
public class ProductRepository
{
    private readonly CosmosDbContext _context;

    public async Task<List<Product>> GetAllAsync()
    {
        return await _context.Products.ToListAsync();
    }

    public async Task<Product> GetByIdAsync(int id)
    {
        return await _context.Products.FirstAsync(p => p.Id == id);
    }

    public async Task<int> GetCountAsync()
    {
        return await _context.Products.CountAsync();
    }

    public async Task SaveAsync(Product product)
    {
        _context.Products.Add(product);
        await _context.SaveChangesAsync();
    }
}
```

**Key points:**
- The `CosmosOptionsExtension.EnableSyncOverAsync()` configuration you had in .NET 10 no longer exists — it won't compile.
- This only affects the **Cosmos provider**; the relational providers (SQL Server, PostgreSQL, etc.) still support sync operations.
- Callers of your repository must propagate `async`/`await` up the call stack.
